The paper deals with the problem of fairly allocating goods among agents with additive valuations, which is a classic problem in game theory (cs.GT). The focus is on the effectiveness of greedy algorithms, which are often studied in the context of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also discusses the optimization of Nash social welfare, which is a common objective in machine learning (cs.LG) and economics (cs.EC).
